-- REGRESSION (2026-07-13, task T28): a REFUTABLE pattern-guard (`Yes x <- a`) on a
-- clause of a MULTI-CLAUSE function.  This was a silent run≠build MISCOMPILE: the
-- interpreter printed the right answer, the BUILT BINARY aborted with
-- `runtime error [E-INDEX-OOB]`.
--
-- Why: desugar lowers a clause's guard chain to a body-level `CDecision` whose
-- wildcard arm is the `__fallthrough__ ()` sentinel ("this clause didn't match —
-- try the next one").  The LLVM emitter took that sentinel's target from a mutable
-- `fallthroughLabelRef`, which `emitDecision` NULLS across any body-level match (so a
-- nested match's own non-exhaustive CTFail is a genuine abort, not a jump to the next
-- clause).  A refutable guard IS such a body-level match — so the null erased its
-- target and "try the next clause" became `@mdk_oob`.  The label now rides in the node
-- (`__ft__<label>`, emit_support's `labelFallthrough` — the design WasmGC already had
-- and which is why WasmGC never had this bug).
--
-- Covers what `guard_refut_ctor.mdk` does not: that fixture pins the MATCH-ARM form
-- (`v if Box w <- x => w`, the CTGuard path).  This is the CLAUSE form, whose guard
-- binder (`x`) is also USED IN THE BODY.
-- one (Yes 7) = 7 ; one No = 0 (falls through to clause 2)
data Opt = Yes Int | No

one : Opt -> Int
one a | Yes x <- a = x + 1
one _ = 100

main = one (Yes 7) + one No
